                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc>
                            <supportDesc>
                                <support><term>monument</term> Dyfed Archaeological Trust Historic Environment Record: <ref target="https://archwilio.org.uk/"><idno type="HER">4245</idno>St David's Church</ref>
                                    <material>Stone</material> <objectType>slab</objectType> comprised of <q>medium-grained, bimodal, moderately sorted, clast-supported weak red (10YR 5/3) sadstone with horizontal laminations.</q><bibl><ptr target ="EDW2007"/>Edwards 2007 <citedRange unit="page">294</citedRange></bibl>.
                                    <dimensions unit="m">
                                        <height>1.725</height>
                                        <width>0.43</width>
                                        <depth>0.115</depth>
                                    </dimensions></support>
                                <condition/>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout>The stone is inscribed with <q>two fragmentary ogam inscriptions. The first is on the left angle (A/D) near the top and reads veritcally upwards. The second is in a similar position on the right angle (A/B) and reads vertically downwards... The ogam strokes are finely and lightly <rs type="execution" key="incised" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/1.html">incised.</rs></q> There is also a <q><rs type="execution" key="incised" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/1.html">medium-incised</rs>, roman-letter, Latin inscription set horizontally in eight lines.</q><bibl><ptr target ="EDW2007"/>Edwards 2007 <citedRange unit="page">294</citedRange></bibl>.</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote><q>The [latin] inscription is in book-script... Some letters have triangular or bifid serifs. There are variations in the forms of some letters. ET, EX and AE are ligatures; GN and TI are conjoined... An inscription remarkable for the evenness of its book-script. The letter-forms are carefully controlled and tend to be made as square as possible, with several geometric forms (F, G, N, S, U).</q><bibl><ptr target ="EDW2007"/>Edwards 2007 <citedRange unit="page">294-298</citedRange></bibl>.
                                <height></height>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
