            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <div type="textpart" n="1">
                     <p><title>Ogham</title>: <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/>MAGLI<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown"></gap>DUBR<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown"></gap>
                        <lb n="2" style="text-direction:down"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown"></gap>QI<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown"></gap></p>
                </div>
               </div>
              <div type="textpart" n="2">
                  <p><title>Latin</title>: With the sign of the cross I fashioned on that [?] I ask all walking there that they pray for the soul of <foreign xml:lang="pgl">Catuoconus</foreign></p>
              </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <list type="witDetail">
                        <item n="1">
                        <p><q>The surviving ogam letters suggest a compound personal name: (i) MAGL[-]DUBR, and (ii) -QI-, which could be part of <hi rend="italic">maqi</hi>... The inscription is unlikely to be other than Irish, in view of the use of ogam and the presence of Q... Both DUBAR[CUNAS] and... DUBR[ACUNAS].. seem possible restorations, both being possible spellings of Old Irish <hi rend="italic">doborch√∫</hi>, gen. <hi rend="italic">doborchon</hi>, 'water-dog, otter'.</q> <bibl><ptr target="EDW2007"/>Edwards 2007 <citedRange unit="page">296</citedRange></bibl>.</p></item>
                    <item n="2">
                        <p>CATUOCONI is later Welsh <hi rend="italic">Cadwgan</hi>, a compound of <hi rend="italic">cad</hi>, 'battle', and <hi rend="italic">g(w)ogawn</hi>, 'glory', with a Latin genitive ending added. Both the lettering and the content of the Latin inscription suggest a high level of literacy, though case endings are not always correct... The meaning of <hi rend="italic">illam</hi><q>...cannot be satisfactorily resolved. It has also been cogently argued that some of the unusual features of the Caldy Island 1 inscription can be explained because it is set to metre in the form of rhythmic syllabic adonics, of which it may be the earliest known example.</q><bibl><ptr target="EDW2007"/>Edwards 2007 <citedRange unit="page">298</citedRange></bibl></p></item>
                </list>
            </div>
